Predicting if whether a constructor work has positive or negative cost¶

On this project the goal was to predict if a construction work was going to have a negative or positive cost. This was a real world project, using a company's historic data. The data had around 1100 records.

Importing libraries¶

In [1]:
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import sklearn as skl

Data Quality¶

This dataset had a lot of errors in terms of the quality of the data. It was necessary to insert the data manually in some cases, and that made it very diverse and unformalized. In this step the goal was to simplify and normalize the data. This required a lot of work and knowledge about the data in question.

Bellow will be a sample of the normalization that was done, not everything, because it would be repetitive and long.

Classification¶

After understanding the date, we felt ready to aplly machine learning to it, in order to predict if the costs of a future construcion work would be positive or negative.

Firstly, a cluster was done in order to discover the natural grouping in the data. We found out the appropriate number of clusters to we had to divide our data into. Then we proceeded to visualize the clusters.

In [6]:
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
import numpy as np

kmeans_kwargs = {
    "init": "random",
    "n_init": 10,
    "max_iter": 300,
    "random_state": 42,
}

# A list holds the SSE values for each k
sse = []
for k in range(1, 11):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, **kmeans_kwargs)
    kmeans.fit(df1)
    sse.append(kmeans.inertia_)

From visualizing the different clusters we can see that clusters 1 and 2 are of very small sizes. From this we decided to treat them like outliers and cut them out of the data.

In the Classification part we tested our machine learning models using the python library skl-learn. We used the ROC curve to avaliate our models, the ROC curve consists of a graph confronting the true positive rate (x-axis) with the false positive rate (y-axis). Thus, the coordinate (0,1) represents a perfect classification, that is, 0 false positives and 0 false negatives. Therefore, the area under this curve is a measure of accuracy, and the curve with a larger area represents the best technique, in the view of this measure.
